<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-04-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="765" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d765">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Macallister</persName> to
                                Mr. <persName type="to">Adee</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Consulate of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Barbados</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-04-29"><hi rend="italic">April 29,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 26.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit herewith a
                            letter from Mr. Peter, consular agent at St. Lucia, with stated
                                inclosures<note n="1" xml:id="d765fn1">Not printed. Cites in brief
                                the rules in regard to foreign enlistment and the treatment of ships
                                of belligerents contained in the proclamation of Great Britain. See
                                    <ref target="#pg_865">page 865</ref>.</note> relative to the
                            foreign enlistment act of 1870 and rules thereunder, as applicable in
                            the colony of St. Lucia.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Saml. A. Macallister</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">United States Consul.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>